  #3. copy_tco_env_chain — per-bounce env copying

  At every TCO bounce, the entire env chain is copied from old scope to new. For deep env chains (nested lets, closures), this is O(env_depth) per bounce. A 1000-iteration loop with 5 env frames = 5000 frame copies.

  Dialectic questions: Can envs be immutable/persistent (structural sharing, never copied)? Could we pin env frames that survive bounces? Could scope_gen stamps on Env structs enable lazy copying? What if we used a "stack of
  bindings" instead of a linked list of env frames?

  Why it matters: This is hidden O(n*d) in every TCO loop (n iterations, d env depth). For tight numeric loops it doesn't matter, but for closures-in-loops it's significant.

