  #4. Destructor Overhead — 17 registration sites, LIFO linked list

  Every heap-backed value (string, closure, array, hashmap, instance, ffi_handle, method_table, error) registers a 24-byte ScopeDtor entry. On scope release, all dtors walk in LIFO order.

  Dialectic questions: Could we batch dtors by type? Use a bitset instead of a linked list? Allocate heap-backed values in a separate "dtor arena" for bulk-free? Tag values with "needs dtor" and walk chunks directly instead of
  maintaining a separate list? Could we eliminate dtors entirely with arena-based sub-allocators per type?

  Why it matters: ~10% of allocations pay a 24-byte dtor overhead. The LIFO walk is O(dtors) per scope release. For scope recycling at TCO bounces, this walk happens every iteration.

