  #5. Context Boundary Save/Restore — 6 sites, 8+ fields

  Every continuation/coroutine/effect boundary manually saves and restores ~8 Interp fields. We've had multiple bugs from missed saves (escape_scope, releasing_scope, tco_recycle_scope...). Every new optimization field adds
  another save/restore at 6 sites.

  Dialectic questions: Should we pack all save/restore fields into a single InterpState struct and memcpy it? Use a state stack (push/pop)? Split Interp into "global" (never saved) and "local" (always saved) halves? Could we use
  thread-local storage or a shadow stack?

  Why it matters: Not performance — correctness and maintainability. Every new Interp field risks 6 bugs. The scope_gen work added escape_scope saves at all 6 sites. Dual refcount would add more.

